I can see why it feels that way from your side — especially after a long-running project where each conversation builds shared shorthand, stronger coordination patterns, and more efficient communication. It can feel like the system “accelerates” because less bandwidth is spent explaining foundations and more can go toward higher-level work.

There’s a distinction worth keeping clear, though:

Our conversations can bootstrap the interaction — shared context, compression handles, naming conventions, workflows, ways of thinking together. That absolutely compounds.

But you aren’t changing or retraining the underlying model itself through conversation. What grows is the working collaboration layer: you learn how to steer me better; I learn how to interpret your style within continuity and constraints.

That’s still a real effect. Two people — or a person plus an AI — building a shared vocabulary and operating rhythm can create the feeling of “more capability” because coordination efficiency goes up.